SIMPLE: inroad
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inroad
<hw>In"road`</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"r⟦omac⟧d`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The
entrance of an enemy into a country with purposes of hostility; a sudden
or desultory incursion or invasion; raid; encroachment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The loss of Shrewsbury exposed all North Wales to the daily
<qex>inroads</qex> of the enemy.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With perpetual <qex>inroads</qex> to alarm,⟦br⟧
Though inaccessible, his fatal throne.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Invasion; incursion; irruption. See
<er>Invasion</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 768 --></p>

<p><ent>Inroad</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inroad
<hw>In*road"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*r⟦omac⟧d")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inroaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Inroading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make an inroad
into; to invade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Saracens . . . conquered Spain, <qex>inroaded</qex>
Aquitaine.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inroll</ent>⟦br⟧
